  "prompt": "What does a US green card holder need to travel to Canada?",
  "response": "A U.S. Green Card holder (Legal Permanent Resident) generally needs the following to travel to Canada:\n\n*   **Valid Green Card (Permanent Resident Card - Form I-551):** This is the primary document that proves your status as a U.S. Legal Permanent Resident. Make sure it is not expired and is not damaged.\n*   **Valid Passport:** A valid passport from your country of citizenship is generally required.\n\n**Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Visa Exemption:** Green card holders are generally exempt from needing a Canadian visa for tourism or short visits.\n*   **Citizenship Matters:** While a Green Card generally allows visa-free entry for tourism, your citizenship still matters. There may be different requirements based on your country of citizenship.\n*   **Criminal Record:** Having a criminal record may affect your admissibility to Canada.\n*   **Purpose of Visit:** The information above is for tourism or short visits. If you are planning to work or study in Canada, you will need the appropriate permits or visas.\n*   **Consult Official Sources:** Regulations can change, so always check the official website of Immigration, Refugees and Citizenship Canada (IRCC) ([https://www.canada.ca/en/immigration-refugees-citizenship.html](https://www.canada.ca/en/immigration-refugees-citizenship.html)) for the most up-to-date information and specific requirements based on your citizenship. You can also use their tool to determine if you need a visa: [https://www.cic.gc.ca/english/visit/visas.asp](https://www.cic.gc.ca/english/visit/visas.asp)\n*   **Border Officer Discretion:** Even with the correct documents, a Canadian Border Services Agency (CBSA) officer has the final say on whether you are allowed to enter Canada.\n\n**In summary, always carry your valid Green Card and your valid passport from your country of citizenship. It's best to check official sources like the IRCC website to confirm any specific requirements or if your citizenship affects your entry requirements.**\n",
